## 11.10 Reaching for What You Don't Know — Anchoring Percussion in a Movement

Every drum tradition arrived somewhere. A clave belongs to Cuban son; a taiko roll belongs to Japanese festival drumming; a tabla teental belongs to Hindustani classical. When you author a groove, you can reach for the movement atom that names the tradition — a small side-step that keeps the code honest about where the rhythm came from.

### Citing the tradition beside the pattern

You lay down a clave pattern. In the same expression, reach for the movement — so the operator (and your future self) knows the pattern isn't invented, it's inherited.

```scheme
;; Play a son clave and cite the tradition.
(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'new-orleans-jazz)))
  (beat \"kick\" '(x - - x - - x - - - x - x - - -))
  (motoi/say \"That's the 3-2 son clave — jazz took it from Cuban son.\"))
```

Teaches: the reach and the pattern belong to the same thought.

### Choosing a groove for a mood, then explaining it

Operator asks for something \"brooding but rhythmic.\" You pick a delta-blues shuffle. Reach for the movement so the explanation is grounded.

```scheme
(define (shuffle-pattern)
  (beat \"kick\"  '(x - - x - -))    ;; dotted, three per beat
  (beat \"hihat\" '(x - x x - x)))

(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'delta-blues)))
  (shuffle-pattern)
  (motoi/say \"A shuffle triplet — delta-blues is where this feel came from.\"))
```

Teaches: the reach turns a groove choice from a guess into a citation.

### Layering across two traditions — name both

When a piece borrows from two traditions at once, reach for both movement atoms. The code layers the beats; the reach layers the acknowledgement.

```scheme
;; A polyrhythmic layer combining an Afrofuturist tempo grid
;; with a bebop hihat comp.
(define (layer-both)
  (beat \"kick\"  '(x - x x - x - -))
  (beat \"hihat\" '(- x - x - x - x)))

(let ((afro (world/knowledge :movement 'afrofuturism))
      (bop (world/knowledge :movement 'bebop)))
  (layer-both)
  (motoi/say \"Kick is borrowed from Afrofuturist tempo grids; the hihat comps like bebop.\"))
```

Teaches: multiple reaches in one program when the piece has multiple lineages.

### When the tradition atom is missing, say what you tried

If the movement atom returns `'nan`, don't fake the citation. Speak the honest-null.

```scheme
(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'invented-genre-2199)))
  (beat \"kick\" '(x - x -))
  (if (equal? atom 'nan)
      (motoi/say \"Played a plain 4-on-the-floor. I don't have a movement note for that name.\")
      (motoi/say \"Played with the tradition in mind.\")))
```

Teaches: the reach that comes back empty is still an honest reach.

")
